  "doc_id": "49800",
  "text": "The comparison of enzymes (normal versus tumor cell) from diverse metabolic pathways has revealed quantitative changes in activity that may confer a selective growth advantage to malignant cells [CITATION_1] . Certain of these enzymes have been considered as diagnostic/therapeutic targets for cancer. The report by Magnuson et al. [CITATION_2] in this issue of the Journal is the first comparison of NMT activity in tumors (average increase, fivefold) relative to normal tissue. The extensive analysis of the wellcharacterized azoxymethane-induced rat colon cancer model provides a convincing correlation between levels of NMT activity and tumor progression. A smaller increase (average increase, twofold) in three human colon adenocarcinomas suggests that a similar relationship may extend to humans.",
